WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.976 align:middle line:90%
[THEME MUSIC]

00:00:01.976 --> 00:00:19.689 align:middle line:90%


00:00:19.689 --> 00:00:21.480 align:middle line:84%
>>GEORGE NOORY: Welcome
to "Beyond Belief."

00:00:21.480 --> 00:00:22.350 align:middle line:10%
I'm George Noory.

00:00:22.350 --> 00:00:24.960 align:middle line:10%
And for years I've interviewed
the man you're about to meet,

00:00:24.960 --> 00:00:28.560 align:middle line:10%
Robert Zubrin, who is the
president of the Mars Society

00:00:28.560 --> 00:00:32.040 align:middle line:10%
and Pioneer Astronautics,
an organization devoted

00:00:32.040 --> 00:00:33.960 align:middle line:10%
to getting us into space.

00:00:33.960 --> 00:00:35.502 align:middle line:84%
Robert, always a
pleasure seeing you.

00:00:35.502 --> 00:00:37.835 align:middle line:84%
>>ROBERT ZUBRIN: Thanks for
inviting me to come and talk

00:00:37.835 --> 00:00:38.790 align:middle line:90%
to you again.

00:00:38.790 --> 00:00:41.190 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You have been
fascinated with space

00:00:41.190 --> 00:00:43.350 align:middle line:90%
since you were a little kid.

00:00:43.350 --> 00:00:47.020 align:middle line:84%
What was that one catalyst
that got you really into it?

00:00:47.020 --> 00:00:48.870 align:middle line:90%
>>ZUBRIN: It was Sputnik.

00:00:48.870 --> 00:00:50.800 align:middle line:10%
I was five when Sputnik flew.

00:00:50.800 --> 00:00:51.600 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: Ah.

00:00:51.600 --> 00:00:53.650 align:middle line:10%
>>ZUBRIN: And I was
an early reader.

00:00:53.650 --> 00:00:55.740 align:middle line:10%
I was already reading
science fiction.

00:00:55.740 --> 00:00:58.410 align:middle line:10%
And while the adults may have
been terrified by Sputnik,

00:00:58.410 --> 00:01:00.630 align:middle line:10%
I was over the top
excited about it.

00:01:00.630 --> 00:01:03.030 align:middle line:10%
Because what it meant
was all these stories

00:01:03.030 --> 00:01:05.220 align:middle line:10%
I was reading about
the spacefaring future

00:01:05.220 --> 00:01:07.000 align:middle line:10%
were going to be real.

00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:10.600 align:middle line:84%
And I just got totally into
it and building rockets.

00:01:10.600 --> 00:01:12.860 align:middle line:90%
My dad got me a telescope.

00:01:12.860 --> 00:01:16.590 align:middle line:84%
I did drawings of the Moon
through the telescope.

00:01:16.590 --> 00:01:18.810 align:middle line:84%
And I learned all
the science I could.

00:01:18.810 --> 00:01:21.480 align:middle line:90%
And I was on board.

00:01:21.480 --> 00:01:25.110 align:middle line:84%
And you know, we were
going to the Moon by 1970,

00:01:25.110 --> 00:01:28.860 align:middle line:84%
Mars by 1980, Alpha
Centuri by the year 2000.

00:01:28.860 --> 00:01:30.450 align:middle line:90%
I wanted to be part of it.

00:01:30.450 --> 00:01:34.020 align:middle line:84%
Now of course, we did
realize only the first part

00:01:34.020 --> 00:01:34.890 align:middle line:90%
of that program.

00:01:34.890 --> 00:01:37.050 align:middle line:90%
We got to the Moon by 1970.

00:01:37.050 --> 00:01:41.201 align:middle line:84%
But at exactly that time, and
I was entering college by then,

00:01:41.201 --> 00:01:43.800 align:middle line:84%
the Nixon administration
slammed on the brakes

00:01:43.800 --> 00:01:45.880 align:middle line:84%
and the Mars
program was aborted.

00:01:45.880 --> 00:01:46.680 align:middle line:90%
And all the rest--

00:01:46.680 --> 00:01:47.580 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Came a halt.

00:01:47.580 --> 00:01:49.110 align:middle line:84%
>>ZUBRIN: Came to
a halt. And it was

00:01:49.110 --> 00:01:51.750 align:middle line:84%
one of the great
disappointments in my life.

00:01:51.750 --> 00:01:55.660 align:middle line:84%
And for a while I accepted it
and went and did other stuff.

00:01:55.660 --> 00:01:57.810 align:middle line:84%
But at a certain
point I said nah,

00:01:57.810 --> 00:01:59.412 align:middle line:90%
I'm not going to let this ride.

00:01:59.412 --> 00:02:00.870 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Had we
kept the pace going

00:02:00.870 --> 00:02:04.344 align:middle line:84%
after we stopped going to the
Moon, but had we kept it up,

00:02:04.344 --> 00:02:05.760 align:middle line:84%
could we have been
to Mars by now?

00:02:05.760 --> 00:02:06.840 align:middle line:90%
>>ZUBRIN: Oh, Yes.

00:02:06.840 --> 00:02:11.580 align:middle line:84%
NASA had plans for the first
human landing on Mars for 1981.

00:02:11.580 --> 00:02:13.740 align:middle line:84%
If we had kept
going, we would have

00:02:13.740 --> 00:02:16.690 align:middle line:84%
had a permanent human
settlement on Mars by 1988.

00:02:16.690 --> 00:02:17.490 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Wow.

00:02:17.490 --> 00:02:21.300 align:middle line:84%
>>ZUBRIN: And probably the
first children born on Mars

00:02:21.300 --> 00:02:24.570 align:middle line:84%
would be graduating high
school on Mars right about now.

00:02:24.570 --> 00:02:27.420 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Do we even have a
space program today, Robert?

00:02:27.420 --> 00:02:30.090 align:middle line:84%
>>ZUBRIN: Oh yeah, we
have a space program.

00:02:30.090 --> 00:02:32.970 align:middle line:84%
But only parts of
it are functional.

00:02:32.970 --> 00:02:35.760 align:middle line:84%
The robotic planetary
exploration program

00:02:35.760 --> 00:02:38.940 align:middle line:84%
is quite functional and is
returning exciting results

00:02:38.940 --> 00:02:41.400 align:middle line:84%
from their various probes
to Mars and Jupiter.

00:02:41.400 --> 00:02:45.600 align:middle line:84%
The space astronomy program is
very functional with the Hubble

00:02:45.600 --> 00:02:48.450 align:middle line:84%
Space Telescope, with the
Kepler Space Telescope.

00:02:48.450 --> 00:02:53.430 align:middle line:84%
And this year we may launch
TESS, a new space telescope.

00:02:53.430 --> 00:02:55.470 align:middle line:84%
And then the WEBB
Space Telescope.

00:02:55.470 --> 00:02:56.640 align:middle line:90%
They've got great stuff.

00:02:56.640 --> 00:02:59.820 align:middle line:84%
But the human space flight
program is completely adrift.

00:02:59.820 --> 00:03:02.610 align:middle line:84%
It's been operating
without meaningful goals

00:03:02.610 --> 00:03:04.620 align:middle line:84%
basically since
the end of Apollo.

00:03:04.620 --> 00:03:06.390 align:middle line:84%
We have enough
money we're putting

00:03:06.390 --> 00:03:07.920 align:middle line:84%
into the human
spaceflight program

00:03:07.920 --> 00:03:10.200 align:middle line:84%
to be sending people
to the Moon and Mars.

00:03:10.200 --> 00:03:12.780 align:middle line:84%
But instead, they're just going
up and down to Earth orbit

00:03:12.780 --> 00:03:16.110 align:middle line:84%
and being used as test subjects
by guinea pig scientists

00:03:16.110 --> 00:03:19.770 align:middle line:84%
to measure the effects of zero
gravity on human physiology.

00:03:19.770 --> 00:03:21.030 align:middle line:90%
This is just crazy.

00:03:21.030 --> 00:03:23.810 align:middle line:84%
Astronauts should not be guinea
pigs, they should be explorers.

00:03:23.810 --> 00:03:25.110 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Right, right.

00:03:25.110 --> 00:03:28.020 align:middle line:84%
It's got to be frustrating
for somebody like you.

00:03:28.020 --> 00:03:29.580 align:middle line:90%
>>ZUBRIN: Yeah, certainly.

00:03:29.580 --> 00:03:32.400 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Because I mean, you
have developed your career

00:03:32.400 --> 00:03:35.710 align:middle line:84%
to try to get us to explore and
we're not doing that anymore.

00:03:35.710 --> 00:03:36.510 align:middle line:90%
>>ZUBRIN: Right.

00:03:36.510 --> 00:03:42.120 align:middle line:84%
We need a goal-driven
human spaceflight program.

00:03:42.120 --> 00:03:45.610 align:middle line:84%
And the primary goal at this
point should be humans to Mars.

00:03:45.610 --> 00:03:47.540 align:middle line:90%
Mars is where the science is.

00:03:47.540 --> 00:03:49.000 align:middle line:90%
It's where the challenge is.

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:50.580 align:middle line:90%
It's where the future is.

00:03:50.580 --> 00:03:53.154 align:middle line:84%
And, I must say, that if we
build a hardware set that

00:03:53.154 --> 00:03:54.570 align:middle line:84%
can take us to
Mars, we'll also be

00:03:54.570 --> 00:03:56.944 align:middle line:84%
able to do the Moon and the
near-Earth asteroids as well.

00:03:56.944 --> 00:03:58.620 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Robert, I
am enthralled though

00:03:58.620 --> 00:04:01.920 align:middle line:84%
at the privatization
of space right now.

00:04:01.920 --> 00:04:05.190 align:middle line:84%
It seems that these private
companies are coming along

00:04:05.190 --> 00:04:06.420 align:middle line:90%
like gangbusters.

00:04:06.420 --> 00:04:07.253 align:middle line:90%
>>ZUBRIN: Well, yes.

00:04:07.253 --> 00:04:08.400 align:middle line:90%
They finally are.

00:04:08.400 --> 00:04:11.220 align:middle line:84%
For a while, you
know, in the '80s

00:04:11.220 --> 00:04:13.680 align:middle line:90%
and the '90s it was just talk.

00:04:13.680 --> 00:04:15.870 align:middle line:84%
And to some extent a cop
out for people saying oh,

00:04:15.870 --> 00:04:16.829 align:middle line:90%
we don't need NASA.

00:04:16.829 --> 00:04:18.810 align:middle line:90%
Private people will do it.

00:04:18.810 --> 00:04:22.980 align:middle line:84%
But starting with Elon Musk
and now with Jeff Bezos,

00:04:22.980 --> 00:04:24.870 align:middle line:90%
this stuff is now real.

00:04:24.870 --> 00:04:29.880 align:middle line:84%
And Musk, in particular, has
shown that not only can he

00:04:29.880 --> 00:04:34.150 align:middle line:84%
develop space flight hardware
at one third the cost

00:04:34.150 --> 00:04:37.110 align:middle line:84%
or 1/10 the cost,
one third the time,

00:04:37.110 --> 00:04:40.387 align:middle line:84%
as has become accepted in
the major aerospace industry.

00:04:40.387 --> 00:04:41.970 align:middle line:84%
He's even developed
stuff that they've

00:04:41.970 --> 00:04:46.587 align:middle line:84%
refused to develop ever, such as
reusable spaceflight boosters.

00:04:46.587 --> 00:04:47.670 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: Which is amazing.

00:04:47.670 --> 00:04:48.836 align:middle line:90%
>>ZUBRIN: Yes, it's amazing.

00:04:48.836 --> 00:04:50.960 align:middle line:90%
But you know, here's the thing.

00:04:50.960 --> 00:04:53.882 align:middle line:84%
The problem wasn't that
they couldn't do it,

00:04:53.882 --> 00:04:55.090 align:middle line:90%
not that they couldn't do it.

00:04:55.090 --> 00:04:57.465 align:middle line:84%
The problem was there was no
incentive for them to do it.

00:04:57.465 --> 00:05:00.840 align:middle line:84%
Because the contract
model that NASA

00:05:00.840 --> 00:05:02.760 align:middle line:84%
had put in place with
the major spaceflight

00:05:02.760 --> 00:05:04.500 align:middle line:90%
contractors was cost plus.

00:05:04.500 --> 00:05:07.350 align:middle line:84%
Whatever they did, NASA
would pay them plus 10%.

00:05:07.350 --> 00:05:10.710 align:middle line:84%
So, they were encouraged
to maintain high costs.

00:05:10.710 --> 00:05:14.490 align:middle line:84%
They were encouraged
to increase overheads.

00:05:14.490 --> 00:05:17.100 align:middle line:84%
There was nothing to be
gained by not doing so.

00:05:17.100 --> 00:05:20.560 align:middle line:84%
Whereas Musk spends
his money like it's

00:05:20.560 --> 00:05:22.800 align:middle line:84%
his own, because a
significant fraction of it is.

00:05:22.800 --> 00:05:23.630 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: It is.

00:05:23.630 --> 00:05:24.430 align:middle line:90%
>>ZUBRIN: OK.

00:05:24.430 --> 00:05:29.210 align:middle line:84%
And so, his goal is to produce
things as cheaply as possible,

00:05:29.210 --> 00:05:32.480 align:middle line:84%
both the rockets themselves
and now making them reusable.

00:05:32.480 --> 00:05:34.900 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Does it make sense
to have a reusable rocket?

00:05:34.900 --> 00:05:36.490 align:middle line:90%
>>ZUBRIN: Oh yes, it does.

00:05:36.490 --> 00:05:40.570 align:middle line:84%
And he's only reusing
the first stage,

00:05:40.570 --> 00:05:44.170 align:middle line:84%
so it's basically going to cut
the cost of launch in half.

00:05:44.170 --> 00:05:46.060 align:middle line:84%
If he can reuse
the second stage,

00:05:46.060 --> 00:05:48.640 align:middle line:84%
then we can talk about
cutting the price of launch

00:05:48.640 --> 00:05:51.430 align:middle line:84%
by a factor of 10,
and even ultimately

00:05:51.430 --> 00:05:54.080 align:middle line:90%
by much more than that, by 100.

00:05:54.080 --> 00:05:54.880 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Wow.

00:05:54.880 --> 00:05:55.150 align:middle line:90%
>>ZUBRIN: I mean--

00:05:55.150 --> 00:05:56.150 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Big difference.

00:05:56.150 --> 00:05:59.710 align:middle line:84%
>>ZUBRIN: And also, and once
you get costs down that low,

00:05:59.710 --> 00:06:02.990 align:middle line:84%
if you have a rocket like
what he has built, OK,

00:06:02.990 --> 00:06:06.640 align:middle line:84%
where the first stage
flies into space

00:06:06.640 --> 00:06:08.320 align:middle line:84%
but then comes back
to the landing site

00:06:08.320 --> 00:06:10.480 align:middle line:84%
and then the second
stage goes to orbit,

00:06:10.480 --> 00:06:13.450 align:middle line:84%
if you can go to orbit you can
go halfway around the world

00:06:13.450 --> 00:06:14.700 align:middle line:90%
just as easily.

00:06:14.700 --> 00:06:19.930 align:middle line:84%
So, you're talking about New
York to Sydney in 40 minutes.

00:06:19.930 --> 00:06:21.050 align:middle line:90%
And this is--

00:06:21.050 --> 00:06:21.850 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Wow.

00:06:21.850 --> 00:06:22.650 align:middle line:90%
>>ZUBRIN: Yes.

00:06:22.650 --> 00:06:25.210 align:middle line:84%
So, this is the market
that will ultimately

00:06:25.210 --> 00:06:26.320 align:middle line:90%
lead to cheap spaceflight.

00:06:26.320 --> 00:06:27.820 align:middle line:84%
Because you know,
we only you launch

00:06:27.820 --> 00:06:30.320 align:middle line:84%
about 80 or 90 satellites
a year, worldwide,

00:06:30.320 --> 00:06:31.120 align:middle line:90%
the whole world.

00:06:31.120 --> 00:06:31.450 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Right.

00:06:31.450 --> 00:06:32.250 align:middle line:90%
>>ZUBRIN: OK.

00:06:32.250 --> 00:06:34.240 align:middle line:84%
Now if it was cheaper,
maybe we'd launch 200.

00:06:34.240 --> 00:06:37.030 align:middle line:84%
But in contrast,
we fly thousands

00:06:37.030 --> 00:06:39.760 align:middle line:84%
of airliners every
day, tens of thousands.

00:06:39.760 --> 00:06:42.070 align:middle line:84%
And that's the kind
of frequency you

00:06:42.070 --> 00:06:43.830 align:middle line:84%
have to have if
we're going to make

00:06:43.830 --> 00:06:47.203 align:middle line:84%
spaceflight as cheap as air
flight and as safe as air

00:06:47.203 --> 00:06:49.450 align:middle line:90%
flight.

00:06:49.450 --> 00:06:54.040 align:middle line:84%
But long-distance surface
to surface is that market.

00:06:54.040 --> 00:06:55.660 align:middle line:84%
And that's what
these reusable launch

00:06:55.660 --> 00:06:56.826 align:middle line:90%
vehicles will make possible.

00:06:56.826 --> 00:06:59.607 align:middle line:84%
It's obviously impossible with
expendable launch vehicles.

00:06:59.607 --> 00:07:01.690 align:middle line:84%
I mean, air travel would
be ridiculously expensive

00:07:01.690 --> 00:07:03.850 align:middle line:84%
if they threw away the
airliner after each flight.

00:07:03.850 --> 00:07:05.260 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Yeah, after
each flight, sure.

00:07:05.260 --> 00:07:07.384 align:middle line:84%
>>ZUBRIN: So, it's got to
be reusable to open that.

00:07:07.384 --> 00:07:09.310 align:middle line:84%
But once you do open
that, then you've

00:07:09.310 --> 00:07:12.560 align:middle line:84%
got a market thousands of
times bigger than the satellite

00:07:12.560 --> 00:07:13.360 align:middle line:90%
market.

00:07:13.360 --> 00:07:16.580 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Of the private
guys, Bezos and Musk--

00:07:16.580 --> 00:07:17.380 align:middle line:90%
>>ZUBRIN: Yes.

00:07:17.380 --> 00:07:20.050 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Which one is
doing the better job?

00:07:20.050 --> 00:07:22.300 align:middle line:84%
>>ZUBRIN: Well, at the
moment, Musk is ahead, OK.

00:07:22.300 --> 00:07:23.980 align:middle line:90%
There's no doubt.

00:07:23.980 --> 00:07:28.660 align:middle line:84%
Musk has actually achieved a
flight to orbit numerous times.

00:07:28.660 --> 00:07:30.262 align:middle line:90%
He's also developed a capsule.

00:07:30.262 --> 00:07:31.720 align:middle line:84%
Bezos has also
developed a capsule.

00:07:31.720 --> 00:07:34.120 align:middle line:84%
But Bezos has not
flown to orbit yet.

00:07:34.120 --> 00:07:38.020 align:middle line:84%
The thing is, Bezos is
much richer than Musk.

00:07:38.020 --> 00:07:45.185 align:middle line:84%
So, if Musk should falter,
Bezos can keep going.

00:07:45.185 --> 00:07:48.320 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: But they're obviously
doing this, Robert, for money,

00:07:48.320 --> 00:07:49.120 align:middle line:90%
right?

00:07:49.120 --> 00:07:52.510 align:middle line:84%
Eventually they want to
make money doing this.

00:07:52.510 --> 00:07:54.955 align:middle line:84%
It's not just for
the love of space.

00:07:54.955 --> 00:07:57.330 align:middle line:84%
>>ZUBRIN: Well, I actually
disagree with that assessment.

00:07:57.330 --> 00:07:58.570 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: How come?

00:07:58.570 --> 00:08:02.470 align:middle line:84%
>>ZUBRIN: Well, because, I
mean Musk will make money

00:08:02.470 --> 00:08:04.270 align:middle line:90%
with SpaceX, OK.

00:08:04.270 --> 00:08:07.540 align:middle line:84%
But this guy could make money
with a chain of candy stores.

00:08:07.540 --> 00:08:09.970 align:middle line:84%
He could make money
doing anything, OK.

00:08:09.970 --> 00:08:11.590 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: He's got
the Midas touch.

00:08:11.590 --> 00:08:13.150 align:middle line:90%
>>ZUBRIN: Yes, certainly.

00:08:13.150 --> 00:08:17.110 align:middle line:84%
And so, the question is,
why is he doing SpaceX?

00:08:17.110 --> 00:08:18.880 align:middle line:84%
It would be much easier,
I mean, you know,

00:08:18.880 --> 00:08:22.960 align:middle line:84%
he could be like Donald Trump
and set up casino hotels, OK.

00:08:22.960 --> 00:08:25.720 align:middle line:84%
There's a lot more money with
that and it's a lot lower risk

00:08:25.720 --> 00:08:27.800 align:middle line:90%
than trying to build rockets.

00:08:27.800 --> 00:08:29.770 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And you've got
hard real estate there.

00:08:29.770 --> 00:08:31.450 align:middle line:90%
>>ZUBRIN: And so forth.

00:08:31.450 --> 00:08:34.210 align:middle line:90%
Musk wants to change the world.

00:08:34.210 --> 00:08:38.909 align:middle line:90%
Musk-- he's not Mother Theresa.

00:08:38.909 --> 00:08:45.270 align:middle line:84%
He's not a generous
person in a saintly sense.

00:08:45.270 --> 00:08:49.950 align:middle line:84%
But what he is interested
in is his self-interest

00:08:49.950 --> 00:08:54.540 align:middle line:84%
is he seeking eternal glory
for doing great deeds.

00:08:54.540 --> 00:08:57.164 align:middle line:84%
It's what the ancient
Greeks called kleos.

00:08:57.164 --> 00:08:57.964 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Yeah.

00:08:57.964 --> 00:09:01.720 align:middle line:84%
>>ZUBRIN: It's why
Achilles killed Hector.

00:09:01.720 --> 00:09:05.400 align:middle line:84%
It's you know, that
is what Musk is about.

00:09:05.400 --> 00:09:07.170 align:middle line:84%
He doesn't just want
to do great deeds.

00:09:07.170 --> 00:09:09.570 align:middle line:84%
He wants eternal glory
for doing great deeds.

00:09:09.570 --> 00:09:13.530 align:middle line:84%
But that's basically
the character trait

00:09:13.530 --> 00:09:15.570 align:middle line:84%
of a person who
wants to be a hero.

