and the TESS Space Telescope.

00:11:35.684 --> 00:11:37.850 align:middle line:84%
And we'll be talking about
the great accomplishments

00:11:37.850 --> 00:11:39.680 align:middle line:90%
of the next Mars Rover.

00:11:39.680 --> 00:11:41.300 align:middle line:84%
But the human
spaceflight program

00:11:41.300 --> 00:11:43.730 align:middle line:84%
will not have accomplished
anything in the meantime.

00:11:43.730 --> 00:11:46.250 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Robert, the
PBS program "Space Time"

00:11:46.250 --> 00:11:50.392 align:middle line:84%
talks about a new technology
called him EM Drive.

00:11:50.392 --> 00:11:52.350 align:middle line:10%
>>MATTHEW O'DOWD: The
structure of the EM Drive

00:11:52.350 --> 00:11:56.220 align:middle line:10%
is a tapered copper
cylinder with two flat ends.

00:11:56.220 --> 00:11:58.380 align:middle line:10%
A resonant radiation
field is induced

00:11:58.380 --> 00:12:01.830 align:middle line:10%
inside so microwave
standing waves reflecting

00:12:01.830 --> 00:12:03.540 align:middle line:10%
between the ends.

00:12:03.540 --> 00:12:06.930 align:middle line:10%
The device was invented
by Roger Shawyer in 1999.

00:12:06.930 --> 00:12:09.000 align:middle line:10%
And a couple of similar
proposals followed,

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:13.230 align:middle line:10%
most notably Guido
Fetta's Cannae Drive.

00:12:13.230 --> 00:12:16.530 align:middle line:10%
These fall under the family
of microwave resonant cavity

00:12:16.530 --> 00:12:17.730 align:middle line:10%
thrusters.

00:12:17.730 --> 00:12:21.920 align:middle line:10%
They propose that thrust and
net force in one direction,

00:12:21.920 --> 00:12:24.810 align:middle line:10%
the fat end for
the EM Drive, can

00:12:24.810 --> 00:12:26.520 align:middle line:10%
be achieved by
extracting momentum

00:12:26.520 --> 00:12:30.990 align:middle line:10%
from the internal radiation
field but with no propellants.

00:12:30.990 --> 00:12:32.550 align:middle line:10%
This would be pretty
revolutionary,

00:12:32.550 --> 00:12:34.794 align:middle line:10%
because conventional rocket
engines are fundamentally

00:12:34.794 --> 00:12:36.210 align:middle line:10%
limited by the
fact that they have

00:12:36.210 --> 00:12:41.040 align:middle line:10%
to carry not just an energy
source, but propellant,

00:12:41.040 --> 00:12:45.060 align:middle line:10%
a bunch of mass to shoot out the
back end to push them forward.

00:12:45.060 --> 00:12:47.970 align:middle line:10%
The law of conservation
of momentum demands this.

00:12:47.970 --> 00:12:51.390 align:middle line:10%
Roger Shawyer explains the
EM Drive's alleged thrust

00:12:51.390 --> 00:12:53.730 align:middle line:10%
as resulting from
differential radiation

00:12:53.730 --> 00:12:56.147 align:middle line:10%
pressure between the two ends.

00:12:56.147 --> 00:12:57.980 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You've heard
of this kind of drive?

00:12:57.980 --> 00:12:59.000 align:middle line:90%
>>ZUBRIN: Uh, yes.

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:02.730 align:middle line:84%
Now OK, there's two
separate issues here.

00:13:02.730 --> 00:13:08.100 align:middle line:84%
If you're just talking
about a radiation drive,

00:13:08.100 --> 00:13:10.260 align:middle line:90%
then there's nothing new, OK.

00:13:10.260 --> 00:13:14.370 align:middle line:84%
That is, it's always been known
that electromagnetic radiation

00:13:14.370 --> 00:13:15.750 align:middle line:90%
has momentum.

00:13:15.750 --> 00:13:19.170 align:middle line:84%
It's why solar sails
can get momentum

00:13:19.170 --> 00:13:20.910 align:middle line:90%
by reflecting sunlight.

00:13:20.910 --> 00:13:23.890 align:middle line:84%
And if you have a radio
transmitter and you have a dish

00:13:23.890 --> 00:13:26.520 align:middle line:84%
and you're shooting
it in one direction,

00:13:26.520 --> 00:13:29.140 align:middle line:84%
it will exert some force
in the other direction.

00:13:29.140 --> 00:13:31.620 align:middle line:90%
That is well understood physics.

00:13:31.620 --> 00:13:36.180 align:middle line:84%
The issue is that they're
claiming anomalous thrust that

00:13:36.180 --> 00:13:39.960 align:middle line:84%
is greater than that
amount of thrust, which

00:13:39.960 --> 00:13:42.390 align:middle line:90%
is outside of known physics.

00:13:42.390 --> 00:13:45.780 align:middle line:84%
And the problem that I have
is that the experiments that

00:13:45.780 --> 00:13:48.840 align:middle line:84%
have been done have been
done at such low thrust

00:13:48.840 --> 00:13:52.170 align:middle line:84%
that the measurement trying to
distinguish between what they

00:13:52.170 --> 00:13:56.190 align:middle line:84%
claim and what we do
expect to be there

00:13:56.190 --> 00:14:02.070 align:middle line:84%
is so small that it could be
ascribed to experimental error.

00:14:02.070 --> 00:14:07.530 align:middle line:84%
And since there is no
theory that supports

00:14:07.530 --> 00:14:09.030 align:middle line:90%
the reality of their claims--

00:14:09.030 --> 00:14:12.000 align:middle line:84%
or no accepted theory,
let me put it that way--

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:14.570 align:middle line:84%
at this point, I'm in
a wait and see mode.

00:14:14.570 --> 00:14:16.830 align:middle line:84%
I'm not out there
throwing my hat

00:14:16.830 --> 00:14:22.770 align:middle line:84%
in the air for the EM
Drive, other than what

00:14:22.770 --> 00:14:27.690 align:middle line:84%
was known always, which was
using electromagnetic radiation

00:14:27.690 --> 00:14:29.312 align:middle line:90%
to create photon pressure.

00:14:29.312 --> 00:14:31.770 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Robert, do you think
we should go back to the Moon

00:14:31.770 --> 00:14:33.730 align:middle line:90%
or move on to Mars?

00:14:33.730 --> 00:14:37.800 align:middle line:84%
>>ZUBRIN: Well, I think we
have to set our sights on Mars.

00:14:37.800 --> 00:14:42.440 align:middle line:84%
But we don't need to design
gigantic science fiction

00:14:42.440 --> 00:14:44.460 align:middle line:90%
spaceships to go to Mars.

00:14:44.460 --> 00:14:46.880 align:middle line:84%
We can go to Mars with
essentially the same kind

00:14:46.880 --> 00:14:48.864 align:middle line:84%
of transportation
system that you

00:14:48.864 --> 00:14:50.030 align:middle line:90%
could use to go to the Moon.

00:14:50.030 --> 00:14:51.770 align:middle line:84%
Which means a
heavy lift booster,

00:14:51.770 --> 00:14:55.400 align:middle line:84%
something that could throw
perhaps 50 tons on Trans-Mars

00:14:55.400 --> 00:14:56.475 align:middle line:90%
or trans-lunar injection.

00:14:56.475 --> 00:14:57.940 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: How long is the trip?

00:14:57.940 --> 00:14:59.690 align:middle line:84%
>>ZUBRIN: Well, to the
Moon is three days,

00:14:59.690 --> 00:15:00.980 align:middle line:90%
to Mars is six months.

00:15:00.980 --> 00:15:01.890 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Six months.

00:15:01.890 --> 00:15:02.690 align:middle line:90%
>>ZUBRIN: OK.

00:15:02.690 --> 00:15:04.850 align:middle line:90%
And either way is doable.

00:15:04.850 --> 00:15:06.410 align:middle line:90%
But the thing is this.

00:15:06.410 --> 00:15:10.370 align:middle line:84%
In other words, you design a
coherent Moon-Mars program.

00:15:10.370 --> 00:15:13.190 align:middle line:84%
You design a Moon
mission, not with

00:15:13.190 --> 00:15:16.430 align:middle line:84%
the absolute minimum capability
for getting to the Moon,

00:15:16.430 --> 00:15:18.650 align:middle line:84%
but with a healthy capability
of getting to the Moon

00:15:18.650 --> 00:15:20.150 align:middle line:90%
like we had with Apollo.

00:15:20.150 --> 00:15:22.670 align:middle line:84%
And then you constrain
the Mars mission

00:15:22.670 --> 00:15:25.970 align:middle line:84%
to operate within
the performance

00:15:25.970 --> 00:15:29.390 align:middle line:90%
envelope of that capability.

00:15:29.390 --> 00:15:32.840 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: If we go to Mars
and it takes six months

00:15:32.840 --> 00:15:35.457 align:middle line:84%
to go, how long would we
stay before we'd come back?

00:15:35.457 --> 00:15:37.040 align:middle line:84%
>>ZUBRIN: Well, the
flight plan that I

00:15:37.040 --> 00:15:41.960 align:middle line:84%
prefer is six months out, six
months back, a year and a half

00:15:41.960 --> 00:15:43.050 align:middle line:90%
on the surface in between.

00:15:43.050 --> 00:15:44.030 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: A year and a half?

00:15:44.030 --> 00:15:44.360 align:middle line:90%
>>ZUBRIN: Yes.

00:15:44.360 --> 00:15:45.160 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Wow.

00:15:45.160 --> 00:15:49.400 align:middle line:84%
>>ZUBRIN: OK, in other words,
the cycle is two and 1/2 years.

00:15:49.400 --> 00:15:52.580 align:middle line:84%
And I would prefer to
spend the majority of it

00:15:52.580 --> 00:15:56.120 align:middle line:84%
on the surface of Mars, because
that is where the science is.

00:15:56.120 --> 00:15:57.500 align:middle line:84%
That's what the
mission is about.

00:15:57.500 --> 00:16:00.740 align:middle line:84%
The mission is, you know,
not about spending time

00:16:00.740 --> 00:16:01.850 align:middle line:90%
flying through space.

00:16:01.850 --> 00:16:04.950 align:middle line:84%
It's about doing
exploration on Mars.

00:16:04.950 --> 00:16:08.360 align:middle line:84%
So, you could spend nine months
going and nine months coming

00:16:08.360 --> 00:16:10.700 align:middle line:84%
back, and then you'd be
a year on the surface.

00:16:10.700 --> 00:16:13.340 align:middle line:84%
But I'd rather spend
60% of the mission time

00:16:13.340 --> 00:16:15.440 align:middle line:90%
on the surface than 40%.

00:16:15.440 --> 00:16:17.780 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Let's see how
NASA's plan for going to Mars

00:16:17.780 --> 00:16:20.280 align:middle line:90%
could evolve.

00:16:20.280 --> 00:16:23.310 align:middle line:10%
>>NARRATOR: NASA's path for
human exploration of Mars

00:16:23.310 --> 00:16:26.620 align:middle line:10%
