00:27:17.740 --> 00:27:20.620 align:middle line:10%
And there are pools
of capital there owned

00:27:20.620 --> 00:27:23.380 align:middle line:10%
by people who have a
passionate interest in space.

00:27:23.380 --> 00:27:26.830 align:middle line:84%
The real question though
is what guarantees can they

00:27:26.830 --> 00:27:29.080 align:middle line:84%
get from the Putin regime
that if they build a company

00:27:29.080 --> 00:27:30.280 align:middle line:90%
it won't just be stolen?

00:27:30.280 --> 00:27:31.600 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Right, it could be.

00:27:31.600 --> 00:27:32.260 align:middle line:90%
>>ZUBRIN: And it could be.

00:27:32.260 --> 00:27:33.468 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: He'll nationalize it

00:27:33.468 --> 00:27:36.100 align:middle line:84%
>>ZUBRIN: So, in fact,
the kleptocracy in Russia

00:27:36.100 --> 00:27:40.030 align:middle line:84%
is actually impairing it
from having its own SpaceX.

00:27:40.030 --> 00:27:42.580 align:middle line:84%
And ultimately,
unless they reform,

00:27:42.580 --> 00:27:44.500 align:middle line:84%
it will impair their
national defense,

00:27:44.500 --> 00:27:46.330 align:middle line:84%
because space is a
very important part

00:27:46.330 --> 00:27:48.230 align:middle line:90%
of national defense right now.

00:27:48.230 --> 00:27:50.890 align:middle line:84%
So, the Russians,
the Putin regime

00:27:50.890 --> 00:27:55.630 align:middle line:84%
is going to be
faced with a choice.

00:27:55.630 --> 00:27:57.872 align:middle line:84%
If you want Russia
to remain strong,

00:27:57.872 --> 00:27:59.830 align:middle line:84%
you're going to have to
provide some guarantees

00:27:59.830 --> 00:28:02.260 align:middle line:84%
for private property
and individual rights.

00:28:02.260 --> 00:28:06.340 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: For years you have
been a proponent to get to Mars.

00:28:06.340 --> 00:28:07.240 align:middle line:90%
You don't give up.

00:28:07.240 --> 00:28:08.830 align:middle line:90%
How come?

00:28:08.830 --> 00:28:12.150 align:middle line:84%
>>ZUBRIN: No one ever
won by giving up.

00:28:12.150 --> 00:28:15.790 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: But why do you
want to go to Mars, Robert?

00:28:15.790 --> 00:28:19.300 align:middle line:84%
>>ZUBRIN: Why do I want
to see people on Mars?

00:28:19.300 --> 00:28:20.560 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Yes.

00:28:20.560 --> 00:28:23.420 align:middle line:10%
>>ZUBRIN: Because at one point
in my life, me going to Mars

00:28:23.420 --> 00:28:24.519 align:middle line:10%
was a real possibility.

00:28:24.519 --> 00:28:26.560 align:middle line:84%
But I don't think that's
realistic at this point.

00:28:26.560 --> 00:28:29.230 align:middle line:90%
I'm already 65.

00:28:29.230 --> 00:28:31.480 align:middle line:90%
We've wasted too much time.

00:28:31.480 --> 00:28:36.140 align:middle line:84%
But if I can have a significant
part in helping make it happen,

00:28:36.140 --> 00:28:38.080 align:middle line:90%
that's good enough for me.

00:28:38.080 --> 00:28:41.924 align:middle line:84%
Because I think it's
the most important thing

00:28:41.924 --> 00:28:43.090 align:middle line:90%
going on in the world right.

00:28:43.090 --> 00:28:44.089 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: It is exciting.

00:28:44.089 --> 00:28:46.520 align:middle line:84%
>>ZUBRIN: OK, I mean
look, think about this.

00:28:46.520 --> 00:28:48.460 align:middle line:90%
What happened in 1492?

00:28:48.460 --> 00:28:49.560 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Mr. Columbus.

00:28:49.560 --> 00:28:50.500 align:middle line:90%
>>ZUBRIN: Right.

00:28:50.500 --> 00:28:51.550 align:middle line:90%
That's true.

00:28:51.550 --> 00:28:54.160 align:middle line:90%
And any American would say that.

00:28:54.160 --> 00:28:57.490 align:middle line:84%
That's the only thing
we remember from 1492.

00:28:57.490 --> 00:28:59.290 align:middle line:84%
But other things
happened in 1492

00:28:59.290 --> 00:29:01.150 align:middle line:90%
that were the big headliners.

00:29:01.150 --> 00:29:04.360 align:middle line:84%
The Borgias took over
the Papacy in 1492.

00:29:04.360 --> 00:29:05.420 align:middle line:90%
That was the big coup.

00:29:05.420 --> 00:29:06.670 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: That was a big story.

00:29:06.670 --> 00:29:09.220 align:middle line:84%
>>ZUBRIN: OK, Lorenzo
de Medici died in 1492.

00:29:09.220 --> 00:29:12.010 align:middle line:84%
England and France signed
a peace treaty in 1492.

00:29:12.010 --> 00:29:15.040 align:middle line:84%
If there had been big
time newspapers and 1492,

00:29:15.040 --> 00:29:17.040 align:middle line:84%
those would have
been the big stories,

00:29:17.040 --> 00:29:20.280 align:middle line:84%
not this Italian weaver's son
taking three little boats off

00:29:20.280 --> 00:29:21.080 align:middle line:90%
into the ocean.

00:29:21.080 --> 00:29:23.040 align:middle line:90%
And you know, what's that about?

00:29:23.040 --> 00:29:23.840 align:middle line:90%
Who cares?

00:29:23.840 --> 00:29:26.050 align:middle line:90%
What's the point?

00:29:26.050 --> 00:29:29.800 align:middle line:84%
So, you know, in 1903
the Wright brothers flew

00:29:29.800 --> 00:29:30.850 align:middle line:90%
the first airplane?

00:29:30.850 --> 00:29:33.430 align:middle line:90%
Who was Secretary of State?

00:29:33.430 --> 00:29:34.230 align:middle line:90%
Nobody knows.

00:29:34.230 --> 00:29:35.160 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Nobody knows.

00:29:35.160 --> 00:29:37.240 align:middle line:90%
>>ZUBRIN: OK, you know.

00:29:37.240 --> 00:29:38.890 align:middle line:90%
None of that stuff matters.

00:29:38.890 --> 00:29:42.940 align:middle line:84%
So, you only have a
certain time on Earth here.

00:29:42.940 --> 00:29:44.820 align:middle line:84%
You want to do
something that matters.

00:29:44.820 --> 00:29:48.520 align:middle line:84%
500 years from now I
believe that if we're

00:29:48.520 --> 00:29:51.610 align:middle line:84%
successful in turning
humanity into a spacefaring

00:29:51.610 --> 00:29:53.950 align:middle line:84%
species, if we do
our job, which is

00:29:53.950 --> 00:29:55.690 align:middle line:84%
to have that first
little Plymouth Rock

00:29:55.690 --> 00:29:59.005 align:middle line:84%
settlement on Mars, 500
years now not only will there

00:29:59.005 --> 00:30:01.660 align:middle line:84%
be new branches of human
civilization on Mars,

00:30:01.660 --> 00:30:04.870 align:middle line:84%
but on thousands of planets
orbiting thousands of stars

00:30:04.870 --> 00:30:06.460 align:middle line:84%
in this neighborhood
of the galaxy.

00:30:06.460 --> 00:30:08.320 align:middle line:84%
And when they look
back on this time, what

00:30:08.320 --> 00:30:09.640 align:middle line:90%
are they going to care about?

00:30:09.640 --> 00:30:13.300 align:middle line:84%
Will they care about
which gang of murderers

00:30:13.300 --> 00:30:14.920 align:middle line:90%
came out on top in Syria?

00:30:14.920 --> 00:30:16.690 align:middle line:84%
Will they care about
who was in and who

00:30:16.690 --> 00:30:18.760 align:middle line:84%
was out and this and
that the other thing?

00:30:18.760 --> 00:30:24.190 align:middle line:84%
And you know, who's going
to remember Rex Tillerson?

00:30:24.190 --> 00:30:27.350 align:middle line:90%
I mean, hello.

00:30:27.350 --> 00:30:33.160 align:middle line:84%
But what we did to make their
grant civilization possible,

00:30:33.160 --> 00:30:34.450 align:middle line:90%
that's what will matter.

00:30:34.450 --> 00:30:36.520 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: People still
remember Neil Armstrong.

00:30:36.520 --> 00:30:38.170 align:middle line:84%
>>ZUBRIN: Yeah, they still
remember Neil Armstrong.

00:30:38.170 --> 00:30:39.378 align:middle line:90%
They still remember Columbus.

00:30:39.378 --> 00:30:40.570 align:middle line:90%
It's 500 years ago.

00:30:40.570 --> 00:30:42.040 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Yeah, exactly.

00:30:42.040 --> 00:30:46.460 align:middle line:84%
>>ZUBRIN: And 500
years from now,

00:30:46.460 --> 00:30:48.440 align:middle line:84%
we may have gone to the
Moon to beat the Soviet

00:30:48.440 --> 00:30:49.840 align:middle line:90%
Union to the Moon.

00:30:49.840 --> 00:30:52.100 align:middle line:84%
500 years from now, they'll
remember Neil Armstrong,

00:30:52.100 --> 00:30:55.550 align:middle line:84%
but only history buffs will even
know what the Soviet Union was.

00:30:55.550 --> 00:30:57.770 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And who will
remember the candidates who

00:30:57.770 --> 00:31:00.110 align:middle line:90%
want to go to Mars permanently?

00:31:00.110 --> 00:31:02.600 align:middle line:10%
>>REPORTER: Mars One has
just taken another step

00:31:02.600 --> 00:31:07.220 align:middle line:10%
to bring mankind where it
has never stepped before.

00:31:07.220 --> 00:31:09.910 align:middle line:10%
Meet the Mars 100.

00:31:09.910 --> 00:31:12.680 align:middle line:10%
Just 100 candidates now
remain in a competition

00:31:12.680 --> 00:31:15.364 align:middle line:10%
for a seat on a one way
trip to the red planet.

00:31:15.364 --> 00:31:17.030 align:middle line:10%
>>ZACHARY GALLEGOS:
I want to go to Mars

00:31:17.030 --> 00:31:18.424 align:middle line:10%
not just to be a
part of history,

00:31:18.424 --> 00:31:20.710 align:middle line:10%
but to inspire people
around the world.

00:31:20.710 --> 00:31:22.810 align:middle line:10%
>>REPORTER: Initially,
more than 200,000

00:31:22.810 --> 00:31:25.630 align:middle line:10%
applied for the Mars One
astronaut selection program

00:31:25.630 --> 00:31:27.640 align:middle line:10%
from all over the world.

00:31:27.640 --> 00:31:31.480 align:middle line:10%
About a year ago, that number
narrowed to about 1,000.

00:31:31.480 --> 00:31:33.022 align:middle line:10%
That's when we first
met six of them.

00:31:33.022 --> 00:31:34.854 align:middle line:10%
>>LEILA ZUCKER: I've
wanted to go into space

00:31:34.854 --> 00:31:36.220 align:middle line:10%
since I was three years old.

00:31:36.220 --> 00:31:38.170 align:middle line:10%
>>REPORTER: Out of
this group, just two

00:31:38.170 --> 00:31:40.150 align:middle line:10%
advanced to the final 100.

00:31:40.150 --> 00:31:43.450 align:middle line:10%
Leila Zucker, a married
46-year-old ER doctor

00:31:43.450 --> 00:31:46.581 align:middle line:10%
from Washington DC
who is well, excited.

00:31:46.581 --> 00:31:48.580 align:middle line:10%
>>LEILA ZUCKER: Spaceship,
spaceship, spaceship!

00:31:48.580 --> 00:31:52.090 align:middle line:10%
>>REPORTER: And Daniel Carey,
a 53-year-old data architect

00:31:52.090 --> 00:31:54.850 align:middle line:10%
from Virginia, husband
and father of two.

00:31:54.850 --> 00:31:57.160 align:middle line:10%
>>DANIEL CAREY: The whole
impact and possibility

00:31:57.160 --> 00:31:59.230 align:middle line:10%
becomes a lot more
real and sharp

00:31:59.230 --> 00:32:01.540 align:middle line:10%
as the numbers get smaller.

00:32:01.540 --> 00:32:03.902 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Are these
people serious?

00:32:03.902 --> 00:32:06.640 align:middle line:84%
>>ZUBRIN: Um,
well, I don't think

00:32:06.640 --> 00:32:09.580 align:middle line:84%
that Mars One is going to
succeed in sending people

00:32:09.580 --> 00:32:12.836 align:middle line:84%
to Mars because they don't
have the financial resources.

00:32:12.836 --> 00:32:13.960 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: To get them there.

00:32:13.960 --> 00:32:14.918 align:middle line:90%
>>ZUBRIN: That's right.

00:32:14.918 --> 00:32:18.490 align:middle line:84%
But they did inspire
a lot of people

00:32:18.490 --> 00:32:20.920 align:middle line:84%
with the visions of
human settlement of Mars.

00:32:20.920 --> 00:32:25.150 align:middle line:84%
And I've met a fair number
of these Mars One final 100.

00:32:25.150 --> 00:32:28.510 align:middle line:84%
And a lot of them are
very credible people.

00:32:28.510 --> 00:32:33.280 align:middle line:84%
I would say of that
final 100, 20 or 30

00:32:33.280 --> 00:32:36.070 align:middle line:84%
would absolutely be qualified
to make the NASA astronaut core.

00:32:36.070 --> 00:32:37.510 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You'd feel honored
to send them, wouldn't you.

00:32:37.510 --> 00:32:38.468 align:middle line:90%
>>ZUBRIN: That's right.

00:32:38.468 --> 00:32:43.870 align:middle line:84%
And we had two of them
actually participate

00:32:43.870 --> 00:32:47.440 align:middle line:84%
in the Mars Society's recent
expedition to the Arctic

00:32:47.440 --> 00:32:49.900 align:middle line:84%
where we did a simulated
Mars mission up there.

00:32:49.900 --> 00:33:02.570 align:middle line:84%
So, no, you know, Mars One
is visionary in the sense

00:33:02.570 --> 00:33:05.330 align:middle line:84%
that Bas Lansdorp does not
have the resources to make

00:33:05.330 --> 00:33:06.180 align:middle line:90%
it happen.

00:33:06.180 --> 00:33:13.190 align:middle line:84%
But I do think that the idea of
a privately funded Mars colony

00:33:13.190 --> 00:33:14.060 align:middle line:90%
is possible.

00:33:14.060 --> 00:33:17.150 align:middle line:84%
I do think that sending
people to Mars one-way

00:33:17.150 --> 00:33:19.820 align:middle line:90%
to create a colony is possible.

00:33:19.820 --> 00:33:21.770 align:middle line:90%
Colonization is a one-way trip.

00:33:21.770 --> 00:33:24.720 align:middle line:90%
Life's a one way trip.

00:33:24.720 --> 00:33:26.450 align:middle line:84%
But I think it
would take someone

00:33:26.450 --> 00:33:31.410 align:middle line:84%
with more resources and personal
connections and other things

00:33:31.410 --> 00:33:32.210 align:middle line:90%
to make it work.

00:33:32.210 --> 00:33:34.820 align:middle line:84%
Just like there
were a lot of people

00:33:34.820 --> 00:33:36.950 align:middle line:84%
who wanted to start
their own space launch

00:33:36.950 --> 00:33:37.915 align:middle line:90%
company before SpaceX.

00:33:37.915 --> 00:33:40.040 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Right, but they
didn't have the resources.

00:33:40.040 --> 00:33:41.748 align:middle line:84%
>>ZUBRIN: They didn't
have the resources.

00:33:41.748 --> 00:33:43.335 align:middle line:84%
Musk was the first
one who really did.

00:33:43.335 --> 00:33:44.135 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Yeah.

00:33:44.135 --> 00:33:50.110 align:middle line:84%
>>ZUBRIN: And so, he's
laid out a vision.

00:33:50.110 --> 00:33:52.830 align:middle line:84%
He's created a dream,
just like the people

00:33:52.830 --> 00:33:57.540 align:middle line:84%
who created the dream of the
private space launch company.

00:33:57.540 --> 00:33:58.590 align:middle line:90%
They tried.

00:33:58.590 --> 00:33:59.700 align:middle line:90%
They failed.

00:33:59.700 --> 00:34:06.250 align:middle line:84%
But ultimately, you know, Elon
Musk saw that and he said,

00:34:06.250 --> 00:34:07.190 align:middle line:90%
I could do this.

00:34:07.190 --> 00:34:07.410 align:middle line:90%
And did it.

00:34:07.410 --> 00:34:09.480 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: What do we find
if we go to Mars, Robert?

00:34:09.480 --> 00:34:10.440 align:middle line:90%
What do we really find?

00:34:10.440 --> 00:34:12.460 align:middle line:90%
Do we see a past civilization?

00:34:12.460 --> 00:34:14.739 align:middle line:90%
What do we find?

00:34:14.739 --> 00:34:16.699 align:middle line:90%
>>ZUBRIN: Well, we find--

00:34:16.699 --> 00:34:18.717 align:middle line:84%
OK, first of all, there's
two different things

00:34:18.717 --> 00:34:20.550 align:middle line:84%
that have to do with
Mars and they both bear

00:34:20.550 --> 00:34:21.900 align:middle line:90%
on the question of life.

00:34:21.900 --> 00:34:24.490 align:middle line:84%
One is life in the past and the
other is life in the future.

00:34:24.490 --> 00:34:25.290 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:34:25.290 --> 00:34:27.980 align:middle line:84%
Now, in terms of
life in the past,

00:34:27.980 --> 00:34:30.330 align:middle line:84%
OK, Mars was once a
warm and wet planet.

00:34:30.330 --> 00:34:32.949 align:middle line:90%
It could have evolved life.

00:34:32.949 --> 00:34:36.090 align:middle line:10%
Mars was warm and wet 3
and 1/2 billion years ago

00:34:36.090 --> 00:34:39.238 align:middle line:10%
at the same time that
life appeared on Earth.

00:34:39.238 --> 00:34:40.154 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: That's right.

00:34:40.154 --> 00:34:42.570 align:middle line:84%
>>ZUBRIN: OK, now
the question is this.

00:34:42.570 --> 00:34:44.770 align:middle line:90%
Did life appear on Mars?

00:34:44.770 --> 00:34:48.300 align:middle line:84%
And if so, did it
appear indigenously

00:34:48.300 --> 00:34:53.130 align:middle line:84%
and then come to Earth by
natural transfer of material

00:34:53.130 --> 00:34:53.931 align:middle line:90%
by meteoric impact?

00:34:53.931 --> 00:34:54.930 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: A meteor, sure.

00:34:54.930 --> 00:34:56.969 align:middle line:84%
>>ZUBRIN: Did it appear
because life from Earth

00:34:56.969 --> 00:35:02.550 align:middle line:84%
came and colonized Mars
through the same process?

00:35:02.550 --> 00:35:05.550 align:middle line:90%
Did we get two separate origins?

00:35:05.550 --> 00:35:09.300 align:middle line:84%
Or were we both colonized
from the outside?

00:35:09.300 --> 00:35:12.744 align:middle line:84%
And we can resolve
this by going to Mars.

00:35:12.744 --> 00:35:13.910 align:middle line:90%
See, there's a real mystery.

00:35:13.910 --> 00:35:14.910 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And they're
all possible.

00:35:14.910 --> 00:35:16.690 align:middle line:84%
>>ZUBRIN: Yes,
they're all possible.

00:35:16.690 --> 00:35:19.320 align:middle line:84%
And we don't have
any proof right now.

00:35:19.320 --> 00:35:24.020 align:middle line:84%
The one thing we do
know is that there's

00:35:24.020 --> 00:35:26.510 align:middle line:84%
something very suspicious
about life on Earth,

00:35:26.510 --> 00:35:29.750 align:middle line:84%
which is that it appears
virtually as soon as it could.

00:35:29.750 --> 00:35:31.790 align:middle line:84%
As soon as the planet
cooled enough to have

00:35:31.790 --> 00:35:35.390 align:middle line:84%
liquid water almost
immediately life appears.

00:35:35.390 --> 00:35:36.910 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: You find that unusual?

00:35:36.910 --> 00:35:39.410 align:middle line:84%
>>ZUBRIN: Well,
that is suggesting

00:35:39.410 --> 00:35:41.570 align:middle line:84%
that it was kind of
around and waiting

00:35:41.570 --> 00:35:46.400 align:middle line:84%
to drop and start as soon
as the place became livable.

00:35:46.400 --> 00:35:47.930 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Maybe it was ongoing.

00:35:47.930 --> 00:35:49.280 align:middle line:90%
>>ZUBRIN: Well, yeah.

00:35:49.280 --> 00:35:51.660 align:middle line:84%
But anyway, but
that is one thing.

00:35:51.660 --> 00:35:54.530 align:middle line:84%
Another thing that's
suspicious about life on Earth

00:35:54.530 --> 00:35:59.750 align:middle line:84%
is we don't find any
what I call pre-bacteria.

00:35:59.750 --> 00:36:02.240 align:middle line:84%
That is, we don't find any
evidence of free living

00:36:02.240 --> 00:36:05.270 align:middle line:84%
organisms on Earth
simpler than bacteria.

00:36:05.270 --> 00:36:06.070 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Right.

00:36:06.070 --> 00:36:07.700 align:middle line:84%
>>ZUBRIN: Now, you
think about this.

00:36:07.700 --> 00:36:13.050 align:middle line:84%
I mean, OK, you think
about an iPhone.

00:36:13.050 --> 00:36:15.240 align:middle line:90%
An iPhone is a machine.

00:36:15.240 --> 00:36:18.680 align:middle line:84%
But there's all sorts of
technologies that proceed it.

00:36:18.680 --> 00:36:22.230 align:middle line:84%
There's computers, there's
electricity, there's batteries,

00:36:22.230 --> 00:36:24.270 align:middle line:90%
there's glass, there's steel.

00:36:24.270 --> 00:36:25.450 align:middle line:90%
There's all these things.

00:36:25.450 --> 00:36:29.620 align:middle line:84%
There's a whole technological
history behind the iPhone, OK.

00:36:29.620 --> 00:36:33.060 align:middle line:84%
Now, so, we can believe
that the iPhone was invented

00:36:33.060 --> 00:36:35.940 align:middle line:84%
by earthlings because they
invented all this stuff that

00:36:35.940 --> 00:36:37.690 align:middle line:90%
led up to it.

00:36:37.690 --> 00:36:45.450 align:middle line:84%
OK, but what if this was the
prehistoric age and people

00:36:45.450 --> 00:36:47.910 align:middle line:84%
had no technologies
beyond stone axes

00:36:47.910 --> 00:36:50.450 align:middle line:84%
and all of a sudden somebody
shows up with an iPhone.

00:36:50.450 --> 00:36:53.280 align:middle line:84%
OK, you would suspect
that must have then came

00:36:53.280 --> 00:36:54.120 align:middle line:90%
from the outside.

00:36:54.120 --> 00:36:54.920 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Had to.

00:36:54.920 --> 00:36:55.870 align:middle line:90%
>>ZUBRIN: OK, right.

00:36:55.870 --> 00:37:02.040 align:middle line:84%
Now, so bacteria may seem
simple compared to big animals

00:37:02.040 --> 00:37:03.370 align:middle line:90%
and plants and people.

00:37:03.370 --> 00:37:04.870 align:middle line:84%
But they're really
very complicated.

00:37:04.870 --> 00:37:07.900 align:middle line:84%
They've got all sorts of
extremely complicated systems

00:37:07.900 --> 00:37:08.700 align:middle line:90%
and subsystems.

00:37:08.700 --> 00:37:12.960 align:middle line:84%
And they got a whole language
of information technology

00:37:12.960 --> 00:37:15.530 align:middle line:84%
in them, DNA, and
RNA and all of this.

00:37:15.530 --> 00:37:17.370 align:middle line:90%
OK, it's all there.

00:37:17.370 --> 00:37:19.410 align:middle line:84%
There had to have been
a prior evolution.

00:37:19.410 --> 00:37:22.290 align:middle line:84%
We find no evidence
of it on Earth.

00:37:22.290 --> 00:37:26.430 align:middle line:84%
OK, so, if we go
to Mars and let's

00:37:26.430 --> 00:37:32.730 align:middle line:84%
say we find bacteria similar to
Earth bacteria, but also more

00:37:32.730 --> 00:37:34.140 align:middle line:90%
primitive organisms.

00:37:34.140 --> 00:37:37.770 align:middle line:84%
So we could see the evolutionary
history from chemistry to life,

00:37:37.770 --> 00:37:40.270 align:middle line:84%
then we'd say, well
life evolved on Mars

00:37:40.270 --> 00:37:43.110 align:middle line:90%
and then it came to the Earth.

00:37:43.110 --> 00:37:47.640 align:middle line:84%
If we were to go to Mars and
find a totally different kind

00:37:47.640 --> 00:37:51.870 align:middle line:84%
of organism that didn't use
DNA and RNA for information,

00:37:51.870 --> 00:37:56.100 align:middle line:84%
then we'd say whoa,
that's a local evolution

00:37:56.100 --> 00:37:57.960 align:middle line:90%
different than Earth evolution.

00:37:57.960 --> 00:38:00.370 align:middle line:84%
And gee, if it could happen
there, it could happen here.

00:38:00.370 --> 00:38:01.828 align:middle line:84%
And I guess maybe
the bacteria just

00:38:01.828 --> 00:38:05.640 align:middle line:84%
wiped out their more primitive
ancestors or something, OK.

00:38:05.640 --> 00:38:08.520 align:middle line:84%
Because this shows that
life could evolve commonly.

00:38:08.520 --> 00:38:12.720 align:middle line:84%
If, on the other hand,
we find only bacteria

00:38:12.720 --> 00:38:15.150 align:middle line:84%
of more or less the same
kind that we have here

00:38:15.150 --> 00:38:17.820 align:middle line:84%
and no pre-bacteria,
that can indicate

00:38:17.820 --> 00:38:20.860 align:middle line:84%
the both Earth and Mars were
seeded from the outside.

00:38:20.860 --> 00:38:22.440 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Which is
a dramatic story.

00:38:22.440 --> 00:38:23.240 align:middle line:90%
>>ZUBRIN: Right.

00:38:23.240 --> 00:38:24.280 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Panspermia?

00:38:24.280 --> 00:38:26.130 align:middle line:84%
>>ZUBRIN: And if
Earth-- yes, panspermia.

00:38:26.130 --> 00:38:28.630 align:middle line:84%
And if Earth and Mars were
seeded from the outside,

00:38:28.630 --> 00:38:31.770 align:middle line:84%
that means all solar systems are
being seeded from the outside.

00:38:31.770 --> 00:38:33.750 align:middle line:84%
It means the universe
is filled with life.

00:38:33.750 --> 00:38:37.800 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Do you think Mars
might have had intelligent life?

00:38:37.800 --> 00:38:40.470 align:middle line:90%


00:38:40.470 --> 00:38:43.260 align:middle line:84%
>>ZUBRIN: No, I actually
don't think that.

00:38:43.260 --> 00:38:44.760 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I could be
wrong about that.

00:38:44.760 --> 00:38:49.170 align:middle line:84%
But the kind of Mars
that we see today

00:38:49.170 --> 00:38:52.350 align:middle line:84%
would not support an
abundant biosphere,

00:38:52.350 --> 00:38:54.640 align:middle line:84%
let alone an intelligent
civilization.

00:38:54.640 --> 00:38:58.867 align:middle line:84%
Now, I do believe that Mars
will host intelligent life.

00:38:58.867 --> 00:39:00.450 align:middle line:84%
I believe when people
go to Mars we're

00:39:00.450 --> 00:39:02.100 align:middle line:84%
going to make Mars
much more habitable.

00:39:02.100 --> 00:39:02.940 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Sure.

00:39:02.940 --> 00:39:04.780 align:middle line:84%
Well, you have a
plan to terraform it.

00:39:04.780 --> 00:39:05.580 align:middle line:90%
>>ZUBRIN: Yes.

00:39:05.580 --> 00:39:07.590 align:middle line:84%
And I think we
will terraform it.

00:39:07.590 --> 00:39:10.140 align:middle line:84%
Because we're a life, and
it's the nature of life

00:39:10.140 --> 00:39:13.800 align:middle line:84%
to take barren environments
and transform them into places

00:39:13.800 --> 00:39:15.720 align:middle line:84%
that are friendly for
the development of life.

00:39:15.720 --> 00:39:19.470 align:middle line:84%
Life has radically
terraformed the Earth.

00:39:19.470 --> 00:39:22.230 align:middle line:84%
The early Earth
resembled the early Mars

00:39:22.230 --> 00:39:27.640 align:middle line:84%
with the CO2 atmosphere
and so forth and no soil.

00:39:27.640 --> 00:39:30.090 align:middle line:84%
It's life that has put
oxygen in our atmosphere.

00:39:30.090 --> 00:39:32.370 align:middle line:84%
It's life that put
soil on the continents.

00:39:32.370 --> 00:39:35.520 align:middle line:84%
It's life, clearly,
that made Earth green.

00:39:35.520 --> 00:39:40.500 align:middle line:84%
And no sooner does any
barren place appear on Earth,

00:39:40.500 --> 00:39:42.480 align:middle line:84%
like Hawaii coming out
of the Pacific Ocean,

00:39:42.480 --> 00:39:44.861 align:middle line:84%
this huge piece of
bare, sterile basalt--

00:39:44.861 --> 00:39:46.110 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: And lifting it's way.

00:39:46.110 --> 00:39:47.818 align:middle line:84%
>>ZUBRIN: --then birds
fly over, and they

00:39:47.818 --> 00:39:49.740 align:middle line:84%
drop seeds and the
place becomes lush.

00:39:49.740 --> 00:39:52.086 align:middle line:84%
And then Polynesians show
up and let loose pigs

00:39:52.086 --> 00:39:53.460 align:middle line:84%
so there's something
good to eat.

00:39:53.460 --> 00:39:55.680 align:middle line:84%
And then Europeans show
up and build hotels

00:39:55.680 --> 00:39:57.330 align:middle line:84%
so there's a nice
place to check in.

00:39:57.330 --> 00:39:59.550 align:middle line:90%
This is what we do.

00:39:59.550 --> 00:40:02.160 align:middle line:84%
And it would be unnatural
if human beings was

00:40:02.160 --> 00:40:05.580 align:middle line:84%
the kind of bird, as it were,
that the biosphere has evolved

00:40:05.580 --> 00:40:08.340 align:middle line:84%
to take the seeds of
life and transport them

00:40:08.340 --> 00:40:11.220 align:middle line:84%
to currently barren
islands across space

00:40:11.220 --> 00:40:12.710 align:middle line:90%
did not do exactly that.

00:40:12.710 --> 00:40:13.710 align:middle line:90%
So we're going to do it.

00:40:13.710 --> 00:40:14.220 align:middle line:90%
We're going to do it.

00:40:14.220 --> 00:40:15.330 align:middle line:90%
We're going to make--

00:40:15.330 --> 00:40:17.280 align:middle line:84%
we're not just going
to bring life to Mars,

00:40:17.280 --> 00:40:18.400 align:middle line:84%
we're going to
bring Mars to life.

00:40:18.400 --> 00:40:20.649 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Will it be government
or these private sector

00:40:20.649 --> 00:40:21.690 align:middle line:90%
companies?

00:40:21.690 --> 00:40:23.790 align:middle line:84%
>>ZUBRIN: Well, I
think initially it's

00:40:23.790 --> 00:40:25.900 align:middle line:84%
going to be a
combination of both.

00:40:25.900 --> 00:40:28.650 align:middle line:84%
OK, I mean look,
look, frankly, SpaceX

00:40:28.650 --> 00:40:29.790 align:middle line:90%
is a combination of both.

00:40:29.790 --> 00:40:32.002 align:middle line:84%
It was started by Musk
with his own money.

00:40:32.002 --> 00:40:33.960 align:middle line:84%
But at this point, I
think about half the money

00:40:33.960 --> 00:40:36.430 align:middle line:84%
coming into SpaceX is
from the government.

00:40:36.430 --> 00:40:39.090 align:middle line:84%
I think the first
human missions to Mars

00:40:39.090 --> 00:40:43.650 align:middle line:84%
will be done with a significant
role by SpaceX hardware.

00:40:43.650 --> 00:40:45.900 align:middle line:84%
SpaceX is going to make
the mission a lot cheaper

00:40:45.900 --> 00:40:48.480 align:middle line:90%
for the American people to do.

00:40:48.480 --> 00:40:50.940 align:middle line:84%
But the government
is still going

00:40:50.940 --> 00:40:52.620 align:middle line:84%
to have to foot
part of the bill.

00:40:52.620 --> 00:40:54.040 align:middle line:90%
But it's like Lewis and Clark.

00:40:54.040 --> 00:40:56.040 align:middle line:84%
