First of all, the radiation
dose rate on the way to Mars

00:46:03.260 --> 00:46:05.960 align:middle line:84%
is a factor of two
larger than what

00:46:05.960 --> 00:46:08.240 align:middle line:90%
it is on the Space Station.

00:46:08.240 --> 00:46:12.320 align:middle line:84%
So, Peggy Whitson just spent
a year on the Space Station.

00:46:12.320 --> 00:46:15.082 align:middle line:84%
She got the same radiation
dose as she would have gotten--

00:46:15.082 --> 00:46:16.040 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Going to Mars.

00:46:16.040 --> 00:46:18.890 align:middle line:84%
>>ZUBRIN: --on a six
month voyage to Mars.

00:46:18.890 --> 00:46:20.972 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And there's
nothing wrong with her.

00:46:20.972 --> 00:46:22.680 align:middle line:84%
>>ZUBRIN: There's
nothing wrong with her.

00:46:22.680 --> 00:46:25.550 align:middle line:84%
And in fact, there's a number of
other astronauts and cosmonauts

00:46:25.550 --> 00:46:27.890 align:middle line:84%
who've done multiple long
missions on the Space

00:46:27.890 --> 00:46:32.090 align:middle line:84%
Station or the Soviet previous
Space Station, the Mir,

00:46:32.090 --> 00:46:35.000 align:middle line:84%
in which they've gotten doses
fully comparable to what

00:46:35.000 --> 00:46:37.380 align:middle line:84%
they would have gotten
going to Mars and back.

00:46:37.380 --> 00:46:41.270 align:middle line:84%
And we see no radiological
casualties among this group.

00:46:41.270 --> 00:46:44.780 align:middle line:84%
And now that's not
to say there isn't

00:46:44.780 --> 00:46:46.790 align:middle line:90%
any increase in cancer risk.

00:46:46.790 --> 00:46:47.840 align:middle line:90%
There is.

00:46:47.840 --> 00:46:50.780 align:middle line:84%
The total cancer risk
you get by going to Mars

00:46:50.780 --> 00:46:55.100 align:middle line:84%
and back would raise your
risk of dying of cancer,

00:46:55.100 --> 00:46:58.830 align:middle line:84%
assuming there's no advance in
medical technique, by about 1%.

00:46:58.830 --> 00:47:00.080 align:middle line:90%
That is the average American.

00:47:00.080 --> 00:47:00.760 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: 1%.

00:47:00.760 --> 00:47:01.730 align:middle line:90%
>>ZUBRIN: That is, yes.

00:47:01.730 --> 00:47:03.620 align:middle line:84%
If you're an average
American and you don't smoke,

00:47:03.620 --> 00:47:05.960 align:middle line:84%
you've got a 20% chance
you're going to die of cancer.

00:47:05.960 --> 00:47:07.520 align:middle line:90%
This would make it 21.

00:47:07.520 --> 00:47:10.790 align:middle line:84%
If you're an average
American smoker, it's 40.

00:47:10.790 --> 00:47:14.490 align:middle line:84%
So, if in fact, we
sent a crew to Mars

00:47:14.490 --> 00:47:16.460 align:middle line:84%
and we recruited
them from smokers

00:47:16.460 --> 00:47:18.860 align:middle line:84%
and we sent them to Mars
without their tobacco,

00:47:18.860 --> 00:47:22.010 align:middle line:84%
we would be reducing their
chance of getting cancer.

00:47:22.010 --> 00:47:23.270 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Interesting stats.

00:47:23.270 --> 00:47:23.600 align:middle line:90%
>>ZUBRIN: Yeah.

00:47:23.600 --> 00:47:26.390 align:middle line:84%
So, one reason to send people to
Mars would be for their health.

00:47:26.390 --> 00:47:30.260 align:middle line:84%
Now, the main health effect that
we've actually seen in space

00:47:30.260 --> 00:47:31.760 align:middle line:84%
has not been from
radiation, it's

00:47:31.760 --> 00:47:34.280 align:middle line:90%
been from zero gravity effects.

00:47:34.280 --> 00:47:38.720 align:middle line:84%
And NASA has studiously resisted
implementing the solution

00:47:38.720 --> 00:47:42.020 align:middle line:84%
to zero gravity, which is
to rotate the spacecraft.

00:47:42.020 --> 00:47:44.120 align:middle line:84%
Because the NASA
space medicine program

00:47:44.120 --> 00:47:47.180 align:middle line:84%
is controlled by zero gravity
health effects researchers.

00:47:47.180 --> 00:47:49.430 align:middle line:84%
So, these people are not
interested in protecting

00:47:49.430 --> 00:47:50.720 align:middle line:90%
the health of astronauts.

00:47:50.720 --> 00:47:54.410 align:middle line:84%
They're interested in getting
research dollars to fill

00:47:54.410 --> 00:47:55.910 align:middle line:90%
their own bowls of rice.

00:47:55.910 --> 00:47:57.410 align:middle line:90%
This is absolute nonsense.

00:47:57.410 --> 00:48:00.710 align:middle line:84%
And these people
who say they want

00:48:00.710 --> 00:48:04.490 align:middle line:84%
to put a space station in lunar
orbit, OK, and put astronauts

00:48:04.490 --> 00:48:09.440 align:middle line:84%
in that so that they
can test the astronauts

00:48:09.440 --> 00:48:12.650 align:middle line:90%
under larger radiation fields.

00:48:12.650 --> 00:48:13.890 align:middle line:90%
OK, this is crazy.

00:48:13.890 --> 00:48:19.550 align:middle line:84%
This is like testing treatments
for wounds by taking soldiers

00:48:19.550 --> 00:48:22.890 align:middle line:84%
and shooting them and then see
how well you can patch them up.

00:48:22.890 --> 00:48:25.850 align:middle line:90%
This is crazy.

00:48:25.850 --> 00:48:29.000 align:middle line:84%
So, once again,
astronauts need to be

00:48:29.000 --> 00:48:31.200 align:middle line:90%
explorers not guinea pigs.

00:48:31.200 --> 00:48:35.030 align:middle line:84%
They're getting on the Space
Station comparable radiation

00:48:35.030 --> 00:48:36.746 align:middle line:84%
doses as they would
get going to Mars

00:48:36.746 --> 00:48:38.870 align:middle line:84%
and back, except they're
not actually going to Mars

00:48:38.870 --> 00:48:39.670 align:middle line:90%
and back.

00:48:39.670 --> 00:48:42.740 align:middle line:84%
I mean, imagine-- you know,
it's one thing to send out

00:48:42.740 --> 00:48:44.900 align:middle line:84%
pilots in bombers
to do an air raid

00:48:44.900 --> 00:48:46.850 align:middle line:84%
and have them risk
the enemy flak.

00:48:46.850 --> 00:48:49.080 align:middle line:84%
It's another thing to have
them in training mission

00:48:49.080 --> 00:48:51.080 align:middle line:84%
flying above your
own city and shooting

00:48:51.080 --> 00:48:54.380 align:middle line:84%
at them with anti-aircraft
guns and take the same risk

00:48:54.380 --> 00:48:57.320 align:middle line:84%
without actually
doing the mission.

00:48:57.320 --> 00:48:59.780 align:middle line:84%
One is ethical,
the other is not.

00:48:59.780 --> 00:49:02.150 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: If you could
convince people and entice

00:49:02.150 --> 00:49:05.792 align:middle line:84%
them to do a Mars program,
how would you do it?

00:49:05.792 --> 00:49:08.000 align:middle line:84%
>>ZUBRIN: I've been trying
to convince the government

00:49:08.000 --> 00:49:11.960 align:middle line:84%
to do it by pointing out the
scientific gains, the gains

00:49:11.960 --> 00:49:13.845 align:middle line:84%
to education by
challenging American youth,

00:49:13.845 --> 00:49:16.220 align:middle line:84%
learn your science, you could
be a pioneer of new worlds.

00:49:16.220 --> 00:49:19.100 align:middle line:84%
We'd get millions of young
scientists from that.

00:49:19.100 --> 00:49:22.430 align:middle line:84%
And by what it means
in terms of America

00:49:22.430 --> 00:49:25.610 align:middle line:84%
putting our stamp on the future
by having a major influence

00:49:25.610 --> 00:49:28.550 align:middle line:84%
in establishing the first new
branch of human civilization.

00:49:28.550 --> 00:49:31.691 align:middle line:84%
If I was to try to convince
private enterprise to do it,

00:49:31.691 --> 00:49:32.940 align:middle line:90%
I've been thinking about that.

00:49:32.940 --> 00:49:35.040 align:middle line:84%
I think what you'd have
to do is the following.

00:49:35.040 --> 00:49:37.248 align:middle line:84%
First of all, we'd have to
have the cost brought down

00:49:37.248 --> 00:49:39.290 align:middle line:84%
substantially by people
like Musk and Bezos,

00:49:39.290 --> 00:49:41.300 align:middle line:84%
which they are in
the process of doing.

00:49:41.300 --> 00:49:43.490 align:middle line:84%
And when the costs are
brought down enough,

00:49:43.490 --> 00:49:44.780 align:middle line:90%
go to Silicon Valley.

00:49:44.780 --> 00:49:47.690 align:middle line:84%
And I say listen guys,
this is what I want to do.

00:49:47.690 --> 00:49:50.510 align:middle line:84%
I want to establish an
inventors colony on Mars.

00:49:50.510 --> 00:49:51.950 align:middle line:90%
You guys invest.

00:49:51.950 --> 00:49:56.210 align:middle line:84%
We will recruit 1,000 of the
most technically accomplished

00:49:56.210 --> 00:49:59.090 align:middle line:84%
people who are totally committed
to the idea of expanding

00:49:59.090 --> 00:50:00.980 align:middle line:90%
humanity to another world.

00:50:00.980 --> 00:50:02.660 align:middle line:90%
And we will send them there.

00:50:02.660 --> 00:50:05.750 align:middle line:84%
And on Mars, they'll have to
invent all kinds of things.

00:50:05.750 --> 00:50:08.565 align:middle line:84%
They'll have to invent
super productive crops

00:50:08.565 --> 00:50:10.940 align:middle line:84%
because their agriculture will
be limited to greenhouses.

00:50:10.940 --> 00:50:12.316 align:middle line:84%
They'll invent
robotic technology

00:50:12.316 --> 00:50:14.356 align:middle line:84%
because there will be a
labor shortage and a need

00:50:14.356 --> 00:50:15.410 align:middle line:90%
for division of labor.

00:50:15.410 --> 00:50:17.360 align:middle line:84%
They'll invent
advanced 3-D printing.

00:50:17.360 --> 00:50:19.190 align:middle line:84%
They'll invent all
kinds of stuff.

00:50:19.190 --> 00:50:20.980 align:middle line:90%
You'll get the patents.

00:50:20.980 --> 00:50:24.654 align:middle line:84%
OK, you know, in other words,
at the frontier where you have--

00:50:24.654 --> 00:50:25.820 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: They get the money.

00:50:25.820 --> 00:50:27.528 align:middle line:84%
>>ZUBRIN: Yes, and
they'll get the money.

00:50:27.528 --> 00:50:30.290 align:middle line:84%
But the frontier is where
people are free to invent

00:50:30.290 --> 00:50:31.340 align:middle line:90%
and forced to invent.

00:50:31.340 --> 00:50:33.440 align:middle line:84%
And we'll send the
best people to do it.

00:50:33.440 --> 00:50:36.320 align:middle line:84%
You know, the American
frontier, 19th century America

00:50:36.320 --> 00:50:40.970 align:middle line:84%
was a massive engine for
technological progress.

00:50:40.970 --> 00:50:44.870 align:middle line:84%
Yankee ingenuity, we
became famous for it, OK.

00:50:44.870 --> 00:50:47.540 align:middle line:84%
Because we were freed of
all sorts of restrictions

00:50:47.540 --> 00:50:50.580 align:middle line:84%
of the old world and we were
in a new and challenging

00:50:50.580 --> 00:50:51.380 align:middle line:90%
environment.

00:50:51.380 --> 00:50:52.850 align:middle line:90%
We were forced to invent.

00:50:52.850 --> 00:50:55.379 align:middle line:84%
Mars will be that
100 times over.

00:50:55.379 --> 00:50:57.420 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Robert, thanks
for being on the program.

00:50:57.420 --> 00:50:58.020 align:middle line:90%
>>ZUBRIN: It's my pleasure.

00:50:58.020 --> 00:50:58.800 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: It's exciting.

00:50:58.800 --> 00:50:59.090 align:middle line:90%
>>ZUBRIN: OK.

00:50:59.090 --> 00:50:59.890 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Let's go.

00:50:59.890 --> 00:51:01.320 align:middle line:90%
>>ZUBRIN: Let's go on to Mars.

00:51:01.320 --> 00:51:02.660 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Would you go?

00:51:02.660 --> 00:51:04.480 align:middle line:90%
>>ZUBRIN: In a heartbeat.

00:51:04.480 --> 00:51:07.090 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Would you come back?

00:51:07.090 --> 00:51:10.510 align:middle line:10%
>>ZUBRIN: You know, the
Marquis de Lafayette

00:51:10.510 --> 00:51:14.280 align:middle line:10%
came to help out in the
American Revolution.

00:51:14.280 --> 00:51:16.770 align:middle line:10%
And he did go back to France.

00:51:16.770 --> 00:51:20.730 align:middle line:10%
But when he went back, he
brought back enough American

00:51:20.730 --> 00:51:23.790 align:middle line:10%
soil to be buried in.

00:51:23.790 --> 00:51:26.760 align:middle line:84%
And actually, he lived
a long time after that.

00:51:26.760 --> 00:51:28.860 align:middle line:84%
He was still alive
50 years later.

00:51:28.860 --> 00:51:31.380 align:middle line:84%
If we were going
to Mars to stay,

00:51:31.380 --> 00:51:33.630 align:middle line:84%
if we were going to Mars
to establish a colony,

00:51:33.630 --> 00:51:35.100 align:middle line:90%
I would go to stay.

00:51:35.100 --> 00:51:37.950 align:middle line:84%
But if we are going to Mars
as part of an expedition

00:51:37.950 --> 00:51:41.680 align:middle line:84%
and we were coming back, I'd
bring back enough Martian soil

00:51:41.680 --> 00:51:42.480 align:middle line:90%
to be buried in.

00:51:42.480 --> 00:51:43.050 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: You would?

00:51:43.050 --> 00:51:43.740 align:middle line:90%
>>ZUBRIN: Yes.

00:51:43.740 --> 00:51:44.130 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: All right.

00:51:44.130 --> 00:51:44.970 align:middle line:90%
How about that.

00:51:44.970 --> 00:51:46.530 align:middle line:90%
Would you go to Mars?

00:51:46.530 --> 00:51:48.240 align:middle line:90%
And would you stay?

00:51:48.240 --> 00:51:51.480 align:middle line:84%
I'm not sure I would give
up all the wonderful things

00:51:51.480 --> 00:51:52.920 align:middle line:90%
on planet Earth.

00:51:52.920 --> 00:51:54.295 align:middle line:90%
But it sure is intriguing.

00:51:54.295 --> 00:51:55.095 align:middle line:90%
I'm George Noory.

00:51:55.095 --> 00:51:57.440 align:middle line:84%
And thanks for watching
"Beyond Belief."

00:51:57.440 --> 00:52:00.190 align:middle line:90%
